 the Lisbon earthquake of 1755, Brown traces the ways presence and power of the nonhuman—weather, natural disasters, animals, even the concept of love—not only influence human creativity, subjectivity, and history but are inseparable from them. Traversing literary theory, animal studies, new materialism, ecocriticism, and affect theory, The Counterhuman Imaginary offers an original repudiation of the centrality of the human to advance an integrative new methodology for reading chaos, fluidity, force, and impossibility in literary culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimals in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHuman beings in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aImagination in literature. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aHISTORY. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh  apetkeeping in literature, geology, Crusoe’s pots, circulation narrative, uncreation, ontology, affect theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501772573?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501772573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501772573/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131922-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishb2023  a